	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Which is the most accurate/REAL NES emulator?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I know BSNES is praised for its efforts in mimicking the SNES hardware as exact as possible - is there an NES equivalent?
<br />
<br />The recent popularity of BSNES in the media has made it somewhat difficult to google search as it returns a lot of SNES related links. 
<br />
<br />I thought this would probably be the best place to ask - sorry if it's the wrong area of the forum, I just registered to ask this question. Thanks!

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>thefox</b> [ Fri Jul 27, 2012 5:09 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Nintendulator and Nestopia are usually considered among the most accurate. According to Bisqwit's <a href="http://tasvideos.org/EmulatorResources/NESAccuracyTests.html" class="postlink">NES accuracy tests</a>, which are based on running multiple test ROMs on various emulators, puNES is the most accurate, with NESICIDE and Bizhawk up there also. However test ROMs can't measure emulation accuracy in all areas. For example, I've noticed something wrong about the audio emulation in puNES. Nintendulator also doesn't emulate the non-linear mixing scheme for the APU.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>3gengames</b> [ Fri Jul 27, 2012 7:28 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I've found FCEUX to be very accurate with what it will allow for the CPU side to be mostly correct, while Nestopia and Nintendulator both have bugs when compared to just what an NES will do. Nintendulator has bad [zp],y writes to MMC1 and probably other mappers, and Nestopia is actually more of a famicom emulator because you can get some bugs to appear that wouldn't happen on an NES, although the bugs are something that can be good because then your program will work on a famicom too.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


